#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:12
msgid ""
"The root filesystem has the immutable attribute set on OSTree installations, "
"so `/`, `/usr` and everything below it is readonly. `/var` is where all the "
"runtime state is kept. There are some symlinks that put the state-carrying "
"directories in their traditional, expected place:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:14
msgid "`/home` → `/var/home`"
msgstr "`/home` → `/var/home`"

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:15
msgid "`/opt` → `/var/opt`"
msgstr "`/opt` → `/var/opt`"

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:16
msgid "`/srv` → `/var/srv`"
msgstr "`/srv` → `/var/srv`"

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:17
msgid "`/root` → `/var/roothome`"
msgstr "`/root` → `/var/roothome`"

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:18
msgid "`/usr/local` → `/var/usrlocal`"
msgstr "`/usr/local` → `/var/usrlocal`"

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:19
msgid "`/mnt`→ `/var/mnt`"
msgstr "`/mnt`→ `/var/mnt`"

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:20
msgid "`/tmp` → `/sysroot/tmp`"
msgstr "`/tmp` → `/sysroot/tmp`"

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:23
msgid ""
"and so on. If you have a separate home partition on your system, it should "
"be mounted on `/var/home`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:27
msgid ""
"For a more detailed explanation of the system layout, refer to the excellent "
"https://ostree.readthedocs.io/en/latest/manual/adapting-existing/[libostree "
"documentation] on this subject."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "Packaging: ostree, rpms, flatpaks and containers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:36
msgid ""
"_ostree_ is responsible for deploying and updating the OS image (ie "
"everything below `/` that is not symlinked into `/var`). ostree also "
"contains the necessary logic to update grub.cfg entries to point to the "
"current image."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:45
msgid ""
"_rpm-ostree_ builds on top of ostree, and makes it possible to install rpms "
"as a 'layer' on top of an ostree image. In practice, that means you can "
"install rpms as usual, just use rpm-ostree install instead of dnf "
"install. What happens under the covers is that rpm-ostree will compose a new "
"OS image by adding the rpm payload to the existing OS image, and creating a "
"new, combined image. To see the newly installed rpms, you have to reboot "
"into the new image. _rpm-ostree_ also takes care of recreating the layered "
"image whenever you update the base OS image."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:48
msgid ""
"_flatpak_ uses container technologies to deploy and run desktop applications "
"isolated from the underlying OS."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:51
msgid ""
"You can of course use other container tools like _podman_ or _buildah_ to "
"run other containers on a Silverblue system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:54
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using Flatpak"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:59
msgid ""
"If you don't want to use the _flatpak_ commandline tools, GNOME Software has "
"excellent support for installing Flatpaks. There are several repositories "
"that provide Flatpaks."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:62
msgid ""
"http://flathub.org[Flathub] is a convenient place to find many popular "
"desktop apps"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:64
msgid ""
"https://sdk.gnome.org/gnome-apps-nightly.flatpakrepo[GNOME nightly] provides "
"builds of unstable GNOME apps"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:66
msgid ""
"https://firefox-flatpak.mojefedora.cz/org.mozilla.FirefoxNightly.flatpakref[Firefox "
"nightly]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:67
msgid "http://eclipse.matbooth.co.uk/[Eclipse nightly]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:71
msgid ""
"Once you have repositories enabled, you can use GNOME Software's excellent "
"support for searching Flatpaks. Or you can use `flatpak search` command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using Package Layering"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:81
msgid ""
"Package layering works by re-composing the OS image locally, while adding "
"extra rpm packages to it. This is done with the `rpm-ostree install` "
"command. Once a package has been layered, rpm-ostree will keep it up-to-date "
"for you and recreate the layer when you install a newer OS image."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:84
msgid ""
"You can also remove a package from OS image. The command to do this is "
"`rpm-ostree override remove`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:88
msgid ""
"rpm-ostree does not currently have an equivalent to the `dnf search` command "
"for finding packages in the configured repositories. As a workaround, you "
"can run _dnf_ in a temporary container like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ sudo podman run --rm fedora:28 dnf search <1>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:93
msgid "provide your search term"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:96
#, no-wrap
msgid "Enabling third-party RPM Repositories"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/first-login.adoc:101
msgid ""
"Silverblue installs a number of yum repositories containing useful software "
"that is not part of Fedora proper for various reasons. You can enable these "
"repositories either during the initial setup of an new install, or from the "
"\"Software Repositories\" dialog in GNOME Software."
msgstr ""
